  "prompt": "I'm 17 year old. How do I know if I have breast cancer?",
  "response": "If you're concerned about the possibility of breast cancer, it's important to know the early signs and symptoms and to seek professional medical advice. While breast cancer is rare in teenagers, it's still a good practice to be aware of your own health and changes in your body.\n\nHere are some signs and symptoms to watch for:\n- **Lump or mass**: The most common sign is a lump in the breast. It may feel hard and have irregular edges, but some may be soft and rounded.\n- **Pain**: Breast pain that is persistent and not related to your menstrual cycle.\n- **Changes in the breast skin**: Look for any redness, scaliness, or thickening of the skin.\n- **Changes in the nipple or breast shape**: This might include nipple discharge (other than breast milk), changes in the shape of the nipple, or inversion (nipple turning inward).\n- **Swelling**: Any unusual swelling in the breast or surrounding areas, including the armpit.\n\nTo assess your situation promptly:\n1. **Self-Examination**: Regularly perform breast self-examinations. Get familiar with how your breasts normally look and feel so you can notice changes.\n2. **Doctor's Visit**: Schedule an appointment with a healthcare provider. A doctor can conduct a physical examination and, if necessary, suggest further testing such as an ultrasound or mammogram.\n\nDo not hesitate to talk to a healthcare professional about any concerns you may have. Early detection and diagnosis are key to effective treatment. Remember that many breast changes are benign, but it's important to get them checked out to ensure your health and peace of mind.",
